KwaZulu-Natal has recorded 1 241 new cases of Covid-19, as at July 1. This brings the total number of cases in the province, since the start of the pandemic in March last year, to 355 847 or 18% of all laboratory confirmed cases. An average of 937 cases, per day, has been recorded in the past seven days. Another 16 people have lost their lives to Covid-19, bringing KZNâ€™s total number of deaths to 10 724. In its daily report, the KZN Department of Health, said the province continues to see an upsurge in the number of cases. The number of hospital isolations is also increasing steadily in both the private and public sector, with numerous patients requiring care in ICU and ventilation. Earlier this week, Premier Sihle Zikalala said six areas in KZN had become epicentres for the deadly new Delta variant of Covid-19. The variant, which was first identified and caused devastation in India, has been found in patients in the Harry Gwala, eThekwini, Zululand, King Cetswayo, Ugu and ILembe districts. There are also signs of a resurgence of the virus in eThekwini, uThukela, uMgungundlovu, Amajuba and Umzinyathi.